body:
### Problem

Luals expects `on_list` in `vim.lsp.buf.document_symbol` to be a function with params as
```
(parameter) options: vim.lsp.LocationOpts.OnList {
    context?: { bufnr: integer, method: string },
    items: vim.quickfix.entry[],
    title?: string,
}
```
Which is incorrect. The output I get from printing the params is
```
      title = "Symbols in plugin/qf.lua"
      context = {
        bufnr = 2,
        client_id = 1,
        method = "textDocument/documentSymbol",
        params = {
          textDocument = {
            uri = "file:///home/user/dots/nvim/plugin/qf.lua"
          }
        },
        version = 0
      },
      items = { {
          col = 7,
          end_col = 9,
          end_lnum = 1,
          filename = "/home/user/dots/nvim/plugin/qf.lua",
          kind = "Variable",
          lnum = 1,
          text = "[Variable] ui"
        }, {
          col = 7,
          end_col = 12,
          end_lnum = 2,
          filename = "/home/user/dots/nvim/plugin/qf.lua",
          kind = "Variable",
          lnum = 2,
          text = "[Variable] signs"
        }, {
[...]
```
`items` is not `vim.quickfix.entry[]` (not even a subset, as `kind` is not from a qf entry), and `content` is missing values.

A quick test with `on_list` in `vim.lsp.buf.references` does return the expected typing:

```
{
  context = {
    bufnr = 2,
    method = "textDocument/references"
  },
  items = { {
      col = 35,
      end_col = 51,
      end_lnum = 1072,
      filename = "/home/user/dots/nvim/plugin/qf.lua",
      lnum = 1072,
      text = "...",
      user_data = {
        range = {
          ["end"] = {
            character = 50,
            line = 1071
          },
          start = {
            character = 34,
            line = 1071
          }
        },
        uri = "file:///home/user/dots/nvim/plugin/qf.lua"
      }
    } },
  title = "References"
}
```

I tested both with lua_ls and rust_analyzer. Spec mentions a `kind` value to be returned (among other things): https://microsoft.github.io/language-server-protocol/specifications/lsp/3.17/specification/#textDocument_documentSymbol

### Steps to reproduce

```
local function symbols()
  vim.lsp.buf.document_symbol({
    on_list = function(options)
      vim.print(options)
      -- or just look at the ls warning about "Undefined field `kind`" when doing `local kind = options.items.kind`
    end,
  })
end
vim.keymap.set('n', 's', function()
  symbols()
end, {})
```

### Expected behavior

Typing should be correct

### Nvim version (nvim -v)

v0.12.0-dev-2019+g94144d4678

### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?

Unrelated

